-- ============================================================
-- Article 1: 50/30/20 Rule
-- ============================================================
(1,
'The 50/30/20 Budget Rule: The Simplest System That Actually Works',
'50-30-20-budget-rule',
'The 50/30/20 rule splits your after-tax income into three buckets — needs, wants, and savings — giving you a guilt-free budget that requires no spreadsheet expertise.',
'/public/blog/50-30-20.png',
'Person reviewing monthly budget categories on paper',
'published',
'[
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"If you have ever opened a budgeting app, stared at 30 empty categories, and closed it immediately — you are not alone. The 50/30/20 rule exists precisely for that moment. It is the antidote to over-complicated budgeting."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"What Is the 50/30/20 Rule?"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The 50/30/20 rule is a percentage-based budgeting framework popularised by U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren in her book <em>All Your Worth</em>. It divides your monthly after-tax income into three simple buckets:"},
  {"type":"list","items":["<strong>50% Needs</strong> — rent, groceries, utilities, minimum debt payments, insurance","<strong>30% Wants</strong> — dining out, streaming services, hobbies, travel","<strong>20% Savings & Debt Repayment</strong> — emergency fund, retirement, extra debt payments"]},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 1: Calculate Your After-Tax Income"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Start with what actually lands in your bank account each month after taxes and payroll deductions. If you are salaried, this is straightforward. If you are freelance or self-employed, use your average net income from the last three months — and remember to set aside for taxes yourself."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 2: Assign the Percentages"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Multiply your after-tax income by 0.50, 0.30, and 0.20 to get your three budget caps. For example, if you bring home $3,500 per month: Needs cap = $1,750 | Wants cap = $1,050 | Savings cap = $700."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 3: Track — But Keep It Simple"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The rule works best when you check in weekly. You do not need to categorise every coffee purchase. Just log your spending in each of the three buckets. SpendScribe lets you create exactly three budget categories and see at a glance which bucket is running hot."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"What If My Needs Exceed 50%?"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"In high cost-of-living cities, needs often run 60–65% of income. That is okay — treat it as a signal, not a failure. The goal is to work toward the 50% threshold over time by increasing income or reducing fixed costs like rent or car payments."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"50/30/20 vs. Zero-Based Budgeting"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Zero-based budgeting assigns every dollar a job, which is powerful but time-intensive. The 50/30/20 rule trades some precision for speed. Use 50/30/20 if you are new to budgeting or just want a quick sanity check. Graduate to zero-based once you have debt to attack or a specific savings goal."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Common Mistakes to Avoid"},
  {"type":"list","items":["Counting gross income instead of net income — always use take-home pay","Putting subscriptions in Needs instead of Wants — streaming, gym, and music apps are Wants","Forgetting irregular expenses like car registration, birthdays, or vet bills — smooth these into monthly averages"]},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The 50/30/20 rule is not perfect, but it is the fastest way to go from no budget to a functioning one. Start this month, revisit in 30 days, and adjust. That simple habit compounds into real financial change."}
]',
'budgeting,savings,personal finance,beginner',
'The 50/30/20 Budget Rule Explained – Simple & Effective | SpendScribe',
'Learn how the 50/30/20 budget rule works, how to apply it to your income, and why it is the simplest budgeting system for beginners and busy people.',
'50/30/20 rule, budget rule, budgeting for beginners, 50 30 20, simple budget, needs wants savings',
7,
NOW(), NOW(), NOW()),

-- ============================================================
-- Article 2: Budgeting on Irregular Income
-- ============================================================
(1,
'How to Budget on Irregular Income: The Freelancer''s Guide',
'how-to-budget-irregular-income',
'Irregular income makes traditional budgeting feel impossible. Here is a system that lets freelancers, contractors, and gig workers build a reliable budget without a steady paycheck.',
'/public/blog/irregular-income.png',
'Freelancer reviewing income on laptop with coffee',
'published',
'[
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Traditional budget advice assumes you get paid the same amount on the same day every month. For freelancers, contractors, consultants, and gig workers, that assumption falls apart immediately. But budgeting on variable income is absolutely possible — it just requires a different approach."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"The Core Problem With Variable Income Budgeting"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Most budgeting systems tell you to plan spending based on this month''s income. When income swings from $2,000 one month to $5,000 the next, that method creates constant anxiety and fails completely in slow months."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 1: Find Your Baseline Income"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Look at the last 12 months of income. Find the three lowest months. Average those three numbers. That is your baseline — the floor you can reliably plan around. Budget only from this number, even in good months."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 2: Build a Buffer Account"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Open a separate savings account you call your ''Income Smoother''. Every month, deposit your full income into this account. Then pay yourself a fixed ''salary'' equal to your baseline. When you have a great month, the buffer grows. When you have a slow month, the buffer covers the gap."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 3: Create a Lean Budget Based on Your Baseline"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Build your monthly budget around your baseline salary, not your best-case income. Cover essentials first — rent, utilities, groceries, minimum debt payments, taxes. Then allocate the remainder to discretionary spending."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 4: Log Every Payment the Day It Arrives"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"With variable income, cash flow awareness is everything. Log each client payment immediately when it hits your account. SpendScribe''s manual entry makes this a 10-second habit. Over time, you build a real picture of your income rhythm — which clients pay early, which pay late, which months tend to be slow."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 5: Budget for Taxes First"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Before allocating a single dollar to spending, set aside 25–30% of each payment for taxes (adjust based on your country and bracket). Move it to a dedicated tax savings account on the same day the payment lands. This money does not exist for spending purposes."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"What About Business Expenses?"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"If you freelance or run a side business, track business expenses separately from personal ones. Create a dedicated budget category for professional tools, subscriptions, equipment, and co-working costs. This makes tax time straightforward and prevents lifestyle expenses from hiding behind ''business'' labels."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"The Mindset Shift That Changes Everything"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Stop thinking in monthly income. Think in annual income divided by 12. When you earn $60,000 in a year, your monthly budget is $5,000 — whether you earn it evenly or in lumpy payments. The buffer account is the mechanical tool that makes this mental model real."},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Irregular income is not a budgeting handicap. It is a superpower when managed correctly — you have income flexibility that salaried workers do not. Build the system once, and it runs itself."}
]',
'budgeting,freelance,irregular income,self-employed,cash flow',
'How to Budget on Irregular Income – Freelancer''s Guide | SpendScribe',
'Learn how freelancers, contractors, and gig workers can build a reliable budget system even with variable monthly income. Step-by-step guide with practical tools.',
'budget irregular income, freelancer budget, variable income budget, gig worker budgeting, self-employed budget',
8,
NOW(), NOW(), NOW()),

-- ============================================================
-- Article 3: Digital Envelope Budgeting
-- ============================================================
(1,
'Envelope Budgeting Without Cash: The Digital Method That Actually Works',
'envelope-budgeting-digital',
'The envelope method is one of the most effective budgeting systems ever created. Here is how to use it digitally — no cash, no physical envelopes, no bank connection required.',
'/public/blog/envelope-budget.png',
'Budget envelopes and coins representing spending categories',
'published',
'[
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The envelope budgeting method is older than credit cards. You take your paycheck in cash, split it into labelled envelopes — one for groceries, one for rent, one for fuel — and when an envelope is empty, spending in that category stops. Simple. Effective. Proven."},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The problem: carrying cash and physical envelopes in 2026 is impractical. But the system''s core logic — pre-allocating money to categories before you spend it — is timeless. Here is how to replicate it digitally without connecting a bank account."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"How Digital Envelope Budgeting Works"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Instead of physical envelopes, you create budget categories with a fixed monthly cap. At the start of each month you ''fill'' each category based on your income. As you spend, you log expenses against the relevant category. When the balance hits zero, you stop — or you consciously decide to borrow from another envelope."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 1: List Your Spending Categories"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Start with 6–10 categories. Fewer is better. Common ones include: Housing, Groceries, Transport, Dining Out, Entertainment, Health, Personal Care, Clothing, Savings, Miscellaneous."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 2: Assign a Monthly Cap to Each Category"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"Base your caps on the last 2–3 months of actual spending, not wishful thinking. If you regularly spend $400 on groceries, budgeting $200 will not work — it will just make you feel guilty. Set realistic caps, then tighten gradually each month."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 3: Log Every Expense Immediately"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The envelope method only works if you log expenses as they happen — or within the same day. Delayed logging leads to ''I think I spent around...'' which defeats the system. Keep SpendScribe open on your phone. Log purchases while waiting for your card to process."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"Step 4: Check Your Balances Mid-Month"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"On the 15th of each month, check every category balance. This mid-point review is what separates people who finish the month on budget from those who do not. If Dining Out is already 80% spent, you know to cook at home for the rest of the month."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"What to Do When an Envelope Runs Out"},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"You have two options: stop spending in that category, or transfer the shortfall from a lower-priority envelope. The key is to make it a conscious decision, not a silent overspend that you discover at month end. Log the transfer and note why it happened."},
  {"type":"heading","text":"The Biggest Advantages Over App-Based Auto-Syncing"},
  {"type":"list","items":["You see every transaction because you enter it — no automatic imports that you never review","The friction of manual entry makes you think twice before spending","No bank credentials are ever shared with a third party","Works for cash, card, and online purchases equally"]},
  {"type":"paragraph","text":"The envelope method is not about deprivation. It is about intention. When you decide upfront how much each category gets, you stop making a hundred small spending decisions and make one big intentional one instead."}
]',
'budgeting,envelope method,manual tracking,spending categories',
'Digital Envelope Budgeting: No Cash, No Bank Sync Required | SpendScribe',
'Learn how to use the proven envelope budgeting system digitally in 2026. Manual tracking, no bank connection needed. Step-by-step guide for any income type.',
'envelope budgeting, digital envelope budget, cash envelope system, budget categories, manual budget',
7,
NOW(), NOW(), NOW()),

